{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Marius Trésor | image = | caption = | fullname = <!-- if different --> | height = {{height|m=1.82}} | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1950|1|15}} | birth_place = [[Sainte-Anne, Guadeloupe]] | position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]] | youthyears1 = 1958–1969 | youthclubs1 = Juventus de Sainte-Anne | years1 = 1969–1972 | years2 = 1972–1980 | years3 = 1980–1984 | clubs1 = [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio]] | clubs2 = [[Olympique Marseille|Marseille]] | clubs3 = [[Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] | caps1 = 92 | caps2 = 253 | caps3 = 93 | totalcaps = 438 | goals1 = 1 | goals2 = 8 | goals3 = 3 | totalgoals = 12 | nationalyears1 = 1971–1983 | nationalteam1 = [[France national football team|France]] | nationalcaps1 = 65 | nationalgoals1 = 4 }}
'''Marius Trésor''' (born 15 January 1950) is a retired [[Defender (association football)|football defender]] from France, who was named by [[Pelé]] as one of the [[FIFA 100|top 125 greatest living footballers.]] He is considered as one of the best central defenders of all time, and he is regarded as one of France's greatest ever players.
Trésor's career began with the French club [[AC Ajaccio|Ajaccio]]. He also played for [[Olympique de Marseille]] and [[Girondins de Bordeaux]]. With Marseille, he won the [[Coupe de France|French Cup]] in 1976. He also won the [[Ligue 1]] title in 1984 with [[Girondins de Bordeaux]]. For the [[France national football team|French national team]], Trésor played in the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]] and [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982]]. He obtained 65 international [[Cap (sport)|caps]], scoring four goals.
