{{EngvarB|date=May 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Infobox stadium | stadium_name= Royal Bafokeng Stadium | fullname= Royal Bafokeng Sports Palace | image= Royal Bafokeng Stadium, Phokeng.jpg | image_size= 250px | location= R565 (Sun City Road), [[Phokeng]], South Africa | coordinates= {{coord|-25.5786|27.1607|format=dms|type:landmark_scale:3000|display=inline,title}} | owner= Royal Bafokeng Nation | tenants= [[Platinum Stars]] | opened= 1999 | renovated= 2009 | expanded= 2009 | seating_capacity= 44,530<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/fifa-world-cup/3547808/Royal-Bafokeng-Stadium|title=Royal Bafokeng Stadium|website=Stuff|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> }}
The '''Royal Bafokeng Sports Palace''' is a [[association football|football]], [[rugby union|rugby]] and [[track and field athletics|athletics]] stadium in [[Phokeng]] near [[Rustenburg]], South Africa. It was built and is managed by the [[Royal Bafokeng Nation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafokeng.com/present/sports-palace |title=Sports Palace &#124; Royal Bafokeng Nation |publisher=Bafokeng.com |accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> It is used as the home stadium for [[Premier Soccer League]] club [[Platinum Stars]]. The [[Leopards (rugby team)|Leopards]] rugby team host large attendance matches during the [[Currie Cup]] at the stadium, instead of their usual home ground, [[Olën Park]].
The capacity of the stadium was increased from 38,000 to 42,000 to be able to host five first round matches and one second round match at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccerlens.com/royal-bafokeng-stadium/43794/|title=Royal Bafokeng Stadium: 2010 Venue – Sportslens|date=4 December 2009|website=''soccerlens.com''|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>
For the 2010 tournament, the main west stand was upgraded and enlarged and given a new [[cantilever]] roof. Other improvements include the installation of new electronic scoreboards, new seats, and the upgrading of the floodlights and public address system.
The stadium upgrade was completed in March 2009 for hosting 4 matches of the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/destination/stadiums/stadium=5007767/index.html|title=FIFA Confederations Cup Russia 2017 - Destination - FIFA|last=FIFA.com|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>
