{{sports-stub}}

'''Tothill Fields''' was an 18th-century area of [[Westminster]] in the county of [[Middlesex]] that lay south of [[St James's Park]] on the north bank of the [[river Thames]]. One of its main features was a [[penitentiary]].<ref>[http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/23575 History of Tothill Fields]</ref>
Between 1735 and 1752, it was the home venue of the [[Westminster Cricket Club]] for [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important cricket matches]]. The earliest known match there was on Saturday, 16 August 1735, when Westminster defeated [[London Cricket Club|London]] by 3 [[wicket]]s.<ref>Buckley, ''FL18C'', p. 11.</ref> Records have survived of two Westminster matches there in 1752, both against [[Addington Cricket Club|Addington]]. The result of the first is unknown and Westminster won the second by 10 [[run (cricket)|runs]].<ref>Buckley, ''FL18C'', pp. 29–30.</ref>
